This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 11/09 hearing reset to 11/07 to secure housing for defendant.
Status conference on November 7, 2022 at 01:00 pm.

11:07 AM 22CF75/22CF91 - Defendant Jade M. Vonbehren appeared by video.  Attorney Steven G. Richards in court for Jade M. Vonbehren.  Attorney Jennifer M. Harper in court for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Harper has spoken with probation and parole; JV is at a treatment program. Attorney Richards states that she is on a 120 day program. JV states that she will be done on November 7 from Laurel House. If discharged, JV will need to be here in person for the next court date.
Status conference scheduled for November 9, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
Status conference on November 9, 2022 at 02:00 pm.

10:02 AM 22CF91/22CF75 - Defendant Jade M. Vonbehren appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Jennifer M. Harper in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Steven G. Richards in court for Jade M. Vonbehren. Attorney Harper ask that the cash bond in 22CF91 be converted to a signature bond for JV to go to treatment and then once treatment  has been complete the bond be converted back to a cash bond. Attorney Richards doesn't object and notes that it is a 120 day program. Attorney Richards asks for a plea/sentencing in 60 days and that JV may appear by video. Court comments and speaks about a waiver that need to be filled out. Attorney Harper doesn't object to JV appear by video and speaks about probation; they may object to a plea and sentencing during the time of treatment. Court asks Attorney Richards will speak to probation about any issues that may occur if plea and sentencing happens during treatment. 

10:13 AM - Court recall the case. Court orders a signature bond $500 for when she leave for treatment and then convert back to a cash bond once JV has completed treatment.
